Anonymous Sat 28 May 2022 19:09:13 No.48082884 Report
Quoted By: >>48082954 >>48083138 >>48083174 >>48086166
I've been working on a new story for a while, and it's started to occur to me that many anthro species would have trouble speaking a large chunk of human languages. As in, they would literally struggle to be able to speak English even if they could comprehend it.

Bilabial sounds would be functionally impossible without a second upper lip that humans and related hominids possess. Anything that would require a short and muscular human tongue or rounded lips are also right out.

Avians would able to circumvent this with their well-developed vocal cords, but barring a similar development, most mammalian species would be SOL and would need to practice ventriloquism in order to speak human languages comfortably, and even then they would be limited.

I would argue that anthro languages, should they develop naturally, would resemble the very few non-bilabial consonant possessing languages in existence: Tlingit, Chipewyan, Oneida, and Wichita.

Also, brass instruments would also be right out, as they require two lips to buzz in order to produce sound. Even many woodwinds would be difficult with just a lower lip seal.

>Question for you anon, what are the parts you find fall into the telling not showing trap?
There are times where you go into too much exposition before really establishing the characters themselves through interaction with their surroundings or other characters, that can be construed as telling instead of showing. Rather than explaining away the setting in your writing you can instead naturally display it through character interactions which lend themselves to bits of exposition without being overly verbose or hamfisted about it.

>Cold Creek was the largest settlement in the territory. It was nestled in the fertile foothills of the White Cap Mountains. So named for the near year-round snow on the mountain peaks that fed into a mighty river. To the North were the tall timbers of the woods, thick and verdant with life. This for example, you're laying out the geography of the area while also giving some notes on the size of the town but not really prompted to at any given moment. A good trick for this is reading your stories out loud to yourself, which also helps with flow, pacing and sentence/paragraph construction.
